{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599280"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:51:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:51:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15537"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15537"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8228"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110811"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8228"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15537"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93002"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19899"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41878"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110811"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe suprarenal (adrenal) glands are paired endocrine organs located in the retroperitoneal space. Their position relative to the vertebral column is asymmetric due to the influence of surrounding organs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the vertebral levels of the right and left suprarenal glands?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T12, T11-T12","T10-T11, T11-T12","T12-L1, L1-L2","T11-T12, T12-L1","T11, T11"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ET12, T11-T12\u003C/strong\u003E vertebral levels represent the correct anatomical positioning of the right and left suprarenal glands respectively. The right suprarenal gland sits lower than the left due to the presence of the liver, which displaces the right kidney and its associated structures inferiorly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET10-T11, T11-T12\u003C/strong\u003E describes positions that are too superior for the right gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET12-L1, L1-L2\u003C/strong\u003E describes positions that are too inferior for both glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET11-T12, T12-L1\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly reverses the relationship, placing the right gland higher than the left.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET11, T11\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly suggests both glands are at the same level, failing to account for the asymmetry caused by the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis asymmetric arrangement is a key anatomical relationship that reflects the influence of surrounding organs, particularly the liver, on retroperitoneal structures. The right suprarenal gland typically sits on the superior pole of the right kidney, while the left suprarenal gland sits on the superomedial aspect of the left kidney.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The right suprarenal gland is positioned at the level of T12 vertebra.","The left suprarenal gland is positioned at the level of T11-T12 vertebrae.","The liver displaces the right kidney inferiorly, causing the right suprarenal gland to sit lower than the left."],"references":["Lotfi CFP, Kremer JL, Dos Santos Passaia B, Cavalcante IP. The human adrenal cortex: growth control and disorders. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Sep 6;73(suppl 1):e473s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e473s. PMID: 30208164; PMCID: PMC6113920","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93002"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15537"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93002"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-03T21:40:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-05T17:45:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8228"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110811"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"